\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {10) Alright, buckle up for an anxious morning FHDM. Big fan of yours, Katherine. I'm such a big fan, that I get this anxious fear of hurting you in some way. I get this fear because my baseline anxiety combines with the fact that I don't know what I'm like in a relationship, and that leads me to chewing on uncertainty about outcomes. And then your therapist was like, "maybe he's severely mentally ill". While I don't think I am severely mentally ill, the objective facts of my life look like red flags and it had me thinking, "wait, what if...". That was one of the reasons I was doing that deeper dive into mental illnesses the past little while, beyond the reasons I mentioned. Amidst all the interesting, if confusing, research, I was idly trying to determine if any of the destructive patterns in the more difficult mental illnesses matched me. Wasn't able to do that. Again, don't think I'm severely mentally ill. HOWEVER, I do have anxiety, and that combined with my great feeling for you has me wanting to reiterate what your therapist was telling you--you deserve an equal relationship. That is also what I want. When I think of us both supporting each other, and the kind of connection that can build, I get very happy feelings. You mentioned how your\~ex made your hard days 10x harder. Well, it would be a DREAM if we can get to the point where we make each other's hard days 10x easier. Life on beautiful mode. From the stories I read, being with someone who has a severe mental illness seems like life on severely difficult mode. The effort to support each other is lopsided. Even without the abuse, that is draining. So, if you ever feel like you are putting more work in than you're receiving, voice it. If that becomes a pattern, *do not hesitate* to split, I will understand. Life is short. Beyond that, if there is ever any pattern of invalidating behavior or general unpleasantness, either towards you, or towards myself, or towards the support you try to give me, again, voice it. Like I'm not expecting perfection from either of us, emotions might flare up at some point as they do in what seems like every relationship, but if there is ever a pattern of lack of accountability and willingness/ability to change, then split. I don't think you need to hear that, because you are sane and vigilant and strong enough to do what is best. All this is just my own anxiety speaking. Like, there were numerous stories of people who got out of a relationship with a person with a mental illness, thought they knew the signs and that they wouldn't end up in that again, but then they fell for someone who had a different illness that presented completely different. And then I get struck dumb the absolute horror of, "what if that happens here? This girl deserves the world, not *that*!". I mean, that's not going to happen, but stay vigilant, and don't play fix-him-up. For what it's worth, I don't think you have to play at anything, because you just being effortlessly you is what helps me. I mean, maybe you're internally putting a shitton of effort into what we've got going on here, but it doesn't seem that way to me. Don't think that's what is happening. I think you're talented ;). }}